Parameter I — Architecture and Agent Design
This parameter evaluates the structural design of each Multi-Agent System, including the total number of agents deployed and the layer architecture through which they operate. It examines the coordination strategy used to manage communication and task delegation between agents, such as sequential pipelines, parallel execution, or graph-based attention mechanisms. Additionally, it assesses the reasoning engine powering each agent, ranging from LSTM and CNN models to Bayesian reinforcement learning and large language models such as GPT-4o.
Parameter II — Data Sources and Integration
This parameter examines the types of clinical data each system ingests, including IoT wearable devices, electronic health records, laboratory results, and medical imaging. It evaluates the real-time processing capabilities of each system and how effectively data is collected, transmitted, and synchronized across distributed nodes. EHR interoperability standards such as HL7 FHIR and SNOMED CT are also assessed to determine how well each system integrates with existing hospital infrastructure.
Parameter III — Privacy and Security
This parameter analyzes the privacy-preserving mechanisms implemented by each system, with particular focus on Federated Learning protocols, Differential Privacy, and Secure Multi-Party Computation. It evaluates regulatory compliance across frameworks such as GDPR, HIPAA, FDA, and IRB standards, and examines the robustness of audit trail implementations including blockchain ledgers, encryption protocols, and runtime governance policies. The risk of data leakage across distributed agent nodes is also compared across all five systems.
Parameter IV — Clinical Performance and Validation
This parameter assesses the quality and rigor of clinical evidence supporting each system, including the study design, sample size, and patient demographics involved in evaluation. It examines primary performance metrics such as diagnostic accuracy, AUROC, HbA1c reduction, and length-of-stay prediction error, alongside the statistical validation methods applied. Systems are differentiated by whether they have undergone real-world patient trials, benchmark dataset evaluations, simulation-based testing, or remain entirely conceptual with no empirical validation.
Parameter V — Explainability and Transparency
This parameter evaluates the depth to which each system integrates Explainable AI tools such as SHAP, LIME, counterfactual reasoning, and uncertainty quantification into its clinical decision-making pipeline. It examines whether explainability mechanisms are native architectural components or post-hoc additions applied only at the output layer, and how effectively they communicate reasoning to clinicians. Human-in-the-loop mechanisms, including escalation protocols and clinician-facing outputs such as dashboards, narratives, and structured assessments, are also compared.
Parameter VI — Scalability and Deployment Readiness
This parameter considers how ready each system is for real-world clinical deployment, distinguishing between systems that have completed real patient pilots, proof-of-concept prototypes, and purely hypothetical frameworks. It evaluates the infrastructure requirements of each system, including edge computing hardware, GPU resources, cloud APIs, and hospital IT integration demands. The adaptability of each framework across multiple clinical domains and its potential for multi-hospital or multi-site scaling are also assessed.
Parameter VII — Ethical and Governance Frameworks
This parameter analyzes the governance model adopted by each system to ensure responsible and accountable clinical AI operation, including IRB approval processes, multi-stakeholder oversight structures, and alignment with WHO ethical guidelines. It examines bias mitigation strategies such as propensity score matching, demographic balancing, adversarial robustness testing, and uncertainty-penalized reward functions. Regulatory clearance status and the uniqueness of each system's ethical contribution — such as EthicMAS-ICU's quantified transparency scoring — are also evaluated and compared.
